<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-2525-353> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "De Sazai hal van Tempel van 500 Arhats, Gohyaku Rakanji. De naam van de hal verwijst naar de grote spiltrap die men moest bestijgen om tot het uitkijkpunt te geraken. De werkelijke naam was Sansôdô, maar de  populaire naam was Sazaidô, een verbastering van Sazaedô, naar de spiraalvorm van de schelp sazae (turbo cornutus - 'gehoornde tulbandschelp'). Uit de serie Edo meisho, 'Beroemde plaatsen in Edo'. Uitgegeven door Fujiokaya Keijiro (Shôrindô) ca. 1844 en 1845. \r\n\r\nThe Sazai Hall of the Temple of Five-hundred Rakan, Gohyaku Rakan Sazaidô, from the series Famous Places of Edo, Edo meisho. Published by Fujiokaya Keijiro, ca. 1844-45.\r\nWoodblock print, horizontal oban, 240 x 363\r\n\r\nThe temple of Five-hundred Rakan is situated on the still largely undeveloped and hardly populated east bank of the central Sumida River. This part of the city partly consists in rice fields and, as here, undeveloped land. The Sazai Hall has a central spiral staircase that would lead to the balcony from where one could enjoy the wide view. It was also popularly known as the ‘Sazae’ Hall, after the resemblance with the sazae shell, an edible horn. In this design, Hiroshige demonstrates his understanding of Western linear perspective that was well-known in Japan at the time." .
